3 Simple regression model

The case in this section is a familiar model of the type \[y=\beta_0+\beta_1 x + \epsilon\].

We will see that within Bayesian approach distribution of \(\epsilon\) does not have to be Gaussian: we will use robust assumption.

Parameterization of the model for MCMC is described on the diagram.

Bayes theorem for this model looks like this: \[p(\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma,\gamma|D)=\frac{p(D|\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma,\gamma)p(\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma,\gamma)}{\int \int \int \int p(D|\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma,\gamma)p(\beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma,\gamma)d\beta_0 d\beta_1 d\sigma d\gamma}\]

3.1 MCMC in JAGS

Read the data, create the data list.

myData = read.csv( file=paste(dataPath,"HtWtData300.csv",sep="/"))
y <- myData$weight
x = myData$height
dataList = list(
    x = x ,
    y = y 
)

Describe the model.

 modelString = "
# Standardize the data:
data {
    Ntotal <- length(y)
    xm <- mean(x)
    ym <- mean(y)
    xsd <- sd(x)
    ysd <- sd(y)
    for ( i in 1:length(y) ) {
      zx[i] <- ( x[i] - xm ) / xsd
      zy[i] <- ( y[i] - ym ) / ysd
    }
}
# Specify the model for standardized data:
model {
    for ( i in 1:Ntotal ) {
      zy[i] ~ dt( zbeta0 + zbeta1 * zx[i] , 1/zsigma^2 , nu )
    }
    # Priors vague on standardized scale:
    zbeta0 ~ dnorm( 0 , 1/(10)^2 )  
    zbeta1 ~ dnorm( 0 , 1/(10)^2 )
    zsigma ~ dunif( 1.0E-3 , 1.0E+3 )
    nu ~ dexp(1/30.0)
    # Transform to original scale:
    beta1 <- zbeta1 * ysd / xsd  
    beta0 <- zbeta0 * ysd  + ym - zbeta1 * xm * ysd / xsd 
    sigma <- zsigma * ysd
}
"
  # Write out modelString to a text file
  writeLines( modelString , con="TEMPmodel.txt" )

Every arrow has a corresponding line in the description.
It is also possible putting description of data as

    for ( i in 1:Ntotal ) {
      zy[i] ~ dt( mu[i] , 1/zsigma^2 , nu )
      mu[i]<-zbeta0 + zbeta1 * zx[i]
    }

That would allow recording mu[i] in MCMC.

Variable names starting with âzâ mean that these variables are standardized (z-scores).
The intention of using z-scores in JAGS is to overcome a problem of correlation of the parameters (see correlation between beta0 and beta1 below).
Strong correlation creates thin and long shape on scatter-plot of the variables which makes Gibbs sampling very slow and inefficient.
HMC implemented in Stan does not have this problem.

parameters = c( "beta0" ,  "beta1" ,  "sigma", 
              "zbeta0" , "zbeta1" , "zsigma", "nu" )
adaptSteps = 500  # Number of steps to "tune" the samplers
burnInSteps = 1000
nChains = 4 
thinSteps = 1
numSavedSteps=20000
nIter = ceiling( ( numSavedSteps * thinSteps ) / nChains )
jagsModel = jags.model( "TEMPmodel.txt" , data=dataList , #inits=initsList , 
                      n.chains=nChains , n.adapt=adaptSteps )
## Compiling data graph

3.2 MCMC in Stan

Describe the model in Stan.

In order to give a vague priors to slope and intercept consider the following arguments:

  1. The largest possible value of slope is \[\frac{\sigma_y}{\sigma_x}\] when variables \(x\) and \(y\) are perfectly correlated.
    Then standard deviation of the slope parameter \(\beta_1\) should be large enough to make the maximum value easily achievable.
  2. Size of intercept is defined by value of \[E[X]\frac{\sigma_y}{\sigma_x}\].
    So, the prior should have enough width to include this value.
modelString = "
data {
    int<lower=1> Ntotal;
    real x[Ntotal];
    real y[Ntotal];
    real meanY;
    real sdY;
    real meanX;
    real sdX;
}
transformed data {
    real unifLo;
    real unifHi;
    real expLambda;
    real beta0sigma;
    real beta1sigma;
    unifLo = sdY/1000;
    unifHi = sdY*1000;
    expLambda = 1/30.0;
    beta1sigma = 10*fabs(sdY/sdX);
    beta0sigma = 10*(sdY^2+sdX^2)    / 10*fabs(meanX*sdY/sdX);
}
parameters {
    real beta0;
    real beta1;
    real<lower=0> nu; 
    real<lower=0> sigma; 
}
model {
    sigma ~ uniform(unifLo, unifHi); 
    nu ~ exponential(expLambda);
    beta0 ~ normal(0, beta0sigma);
    beta1 ~ normal(0, beta1sigma);
    for (i in 1:Ntotal) {
        y[i] ~ student_t(nu, beta0 + beta1 * x[i], sigma);
    }
}
"
stanDsoRobustReg <- stan_model( model_code=modelString )

fitSimRegStan <- sampling(stanDsoRobustReg,

5 Hierarchical regression on individuals within groups

5.1 Simulated data from the book

This example is from Section 17.3 of [K].

In section 2 each individual produced one pair \((x_i,y_i)\).
In panel or longitudinal data each individual, \(j\), produces a sequence of obsevations \((x_{1|j},y_{1|j}),\ldots,(x_{n_j|j},y_{n_j|j})\).
From such data it is possible to estimate regression for each individual \(j\): \(y_{i|j}=\beta_0[j]+\beta_0[j] x_{i|j}\) and, if there is a reason to believe that individuals represent a group that has a common tendency parameters of that tendency can be estimated also.

Examples:

  • Childrenâs reading ability is tested for several years. All children develop reading skills during that period. But each individual child has his or her own learning slopes, while all children as a group may have developmental patterns expressed through higher level patterns
  • In a study of how family income varies with size of the family and in different geagraphical regions. The U.S. Census Bureau has publishe median family income as function as of of persons in the family per state. In this study state plays the role of an individual, the oservations for each individual include sample of family sizes and the corresponding incomes.

A possible model is described on the diagram.

Data come from Student distribution with mean \(\mu_{i|j}=\beta_{0,j}+\beta_{1,j} x_{i|j}\), where index \(j\) shows that each individual has own slope and intercept indexed by \(j\).

All individual slopes come from a single normal distribution with parameters \((M_1,S_1)\).
Similarly, all individual intercepts come from a normal distribution with parameters \((M_0,S_0)\).
Parameters \(M_0, S_0, M_1, S_1\) are estimated and have their own uninformative priors.
All observations have same \(\sigma\) with wide uniform pior distribution.
It is possible to make an individual parameters \(\sigma_j\) with joint prior.

5.1.2 Model description

Description of the model is in the file âch17_2.stanâ:

modelStringPanel = "
data {
    int<lower=1> Ntotal;
    vector[Ntotal] y;
    vector[Ntotal] x;
    int<lower=1> Ngroups;
    int<lower=1, upper=Ngroups> group[Ntotal];
}
transformed data {
    real meanY;
    real sdY;
    vector[Ntotal] zy; // normalized y
    real meanX;
    real sdX;
    vector[Ntotal] zx; // normalized x
    meanY = mean(y);
    sdY = sd(y);
    zy = (y - meanY) / sdY;
    meanX = mean(x);
    sdX = sd(x);
    zx = (x - meanX) / sdX;
}
parameters {
    real<lower=0> zsigma;
    real<lower=0> nu;
    real zbeta0mu;
    real zbeta1mu;
    real<lower=0> zbeta0sigma;
    real<lower=0> zbeta1sigma;
    vector[Ngroups] zbeta0;
    vector[Ngroups] zbeta1;
}
transformed parameters {
    real<lower=0> sigma;
    real beta0mu;
    real beta1mu;
    vector[Ngroups] beta0;
    vector[Ngroups] beta1;
    // Transform to original scale:
    sigma = zsigma * sdY;
    beta0mu = meanY + zbeta0mu * sdY  - zbeta1mu * meanX * sdY / sdX;
    beta1mu = zbeta1mu * sdY / sdX;
    beta0 = meanY + zbeta0 * sdY  - zbeta1 * meanX * sdY / sdX; // vectorized
    beta1 = zbeta1 * sdY / sdX;                                 // vectorized
}
model {
    zsigma ~ uniform(0.001, 1000);
    nu ~ exponential(1/30.0);
    zbeta0mu ~ normal(0, 10.0^2);
    zbeta1mu ~ normal(0, 10.0^2);
    zbeta0sigma ~ uniform(0.001, 1000);
    zbeta1sigma ~ uniform(0.001, 1000);
    zbeta0 ~ normal(zbeta0mu, zbeta0sigma);  // vectorized
    zbeta1 ~ normal(zbeta1mu, zbeta1sigma);  // vectorized
    for (i in 1:Ntotal) {
        zy[i] ~ student_t(1+nu, zbeta0[group[i]] + zbeta1[group[i]] * x[i], zsigma);
    }
}"

5.1.4 Trying to improve convergence by altering step size

Here is a useful blog post addressing similar issue.
It recommends setting parameters controlling step size to shorten steps:

fit <- sampling (model, 
                 data=dataList, 
                 pars=c('nu', 'sigma', 'beta0mu', 'beta1mu', 'beta0', 'beta1', 
                        'zbeta0sigma', 'zbeta1sigma'),
                 iter=50000, 
                 chains = 4, cores = 4,
                 control = list(adapt_delta = 0.999, stepsize = 0.01, max_treedepth = 15)
                 )

Default values are adapt_delta=0.8, stepsize=2, max_treedepth = 11.
With small steps the process runs much longer, but with the same result.

The run with reduced step size is significantly longer.
Again n_divergent__ transactions are reported, so, recommended steps did not help.

The pairs plot shows high correlation between \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) and the problematic points.
By default, draws with below-median accept_stat__ are plotted below the diagonal and those with above-median accept_stat__ are plotted above the diagonal. Each off-diagonal square represents a bivariate distribution of the draws for the inter-section of the row-variable and the column-variable.
Ideally, the below-diagonal intersection and the above-diagonal intersection of the same two variables should have distributions that are mirror images of each other.
Any yellow points would indicate transitions where the maximum treedepth__ was hit, and the red points indicate a transition where n_divergent__ = 1.
Thus, the pairs plot should be used to get a sense of whether any sampling difficulties are occurring in the tails or near the mode.

5.1.5 Gaussian model

Because parameter \(\nu\) of the robust fit indicated distribution very close to Gaussian, replace t-distribution with normal.

5.2 Example from Linear and Nonlinear Models

Example from Linear and Nonlinear Models (31010), lecture 9 considers results of Panel Study of Income Dynamics (PSID) that started in 1968.
Example data psid show income per individual collected over number of years.
The data are in package faraway.

suppressMessages(library(lattice))

Estimate slopes of log-incomes relative to time.
Time interval is centered at 1978.

slopes <- numeric(85);intercepts <- numeric(85)
for(i in 1:85){
lmod <- lm(log(income) ~ I(year-78), subset=(person==i), psid)
intercepts[i] <- coef(lmod)[1]
slopes[i] <- coef(lmod)[2]
}
head(cbind(slopes,intercepts))
##           slopes intercepts
## [1,]  0.08426670   9.399957

## [4,]  0.07585135   7.853027
